● Good question. Here's the full picture:

  Request side (uploads) — still hard-capped at 8 KB

  In connection_thread (chttp.c:595-597):
  char buf[CHTTP_READ_BUFSIZE];   // 8 192 bytes — stack buffer
  int n = recv(fd, buf, sizeof(buf) - 1, 0);  // single recv call
  The entire HTTP request — headers + body — must fit in one 8 KB recv. req->body is just a pointer into buf, so file uploads are
  silently capped at roughly 8 KB minus your headers (~7.5 KB). That's why the memory says "body capped at ~7.5 KB by framework".

  Response side (downloads) — was capped at 64 KB

  HttpResponse.body was char body[65536] — fixed array on the struct. Handlers like handle_download and handle_fs_download_impl did
  fread(res->body, ...) directly into it, and had an explicit guard rejecting files ≥ 64 KB.

  What the plan fixes

  Only the response side. body becomes heap-allocated (char *body + body_cap), so downloads of any size work.

  What the plan does NOT fix

  The request side (uploads). Fixing that is a bigger change — connection_thread would need to:
  1. Read headers first to get Content-Length
  2. Heap-allocate a buffer of that size
  3. Loop-read the body into it

  That's a separate piece of work. Do you want to address uploads too, either now (as an extension to this plan) or as a follow-up?

