● Here's the idea:

  The problem

  connection_thread does a single recv into a fixed 8 KB stack buffer, then req->body is just a pointer into that buffer. There's no
  second read.

  The fix — minimal, clean

  Two-phase read in connection_thread:

  1. First recv into the existing stack buffer — always enough for headers (headers rarely exceed 1-2 KB)
  2. Parse the request from that buffer (unchanged)
  3. Check the Content-Length header
  4. If content_length > req->body_len (body was truncated), heap-allocate content_length bytes, copy the partial body we already have,
  then loop-recv the remainder
  5. Point req->body at the heap buffer and update req->body_len

  Cleanup: add char *body_heap to HttpRequest — NULL normally, non-NULL when the body was extended. After the handler returns,
  free(req->body_heap).

  Changes needed

  ┌──────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │         Location         │                                                 What                                                  │
  ├──────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ chttp.h                  │ Add char *body_heap; to HttpRequest                                                                   │
  ├──────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ chttp.c                  │ After chttp_parse_request, check Content-Length, heap-alloc + loop-recv if body is incomplete, set    │
  │ connection_thread        │ body_heap                                                                                             │
  ├──────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ chttp.c                  │ After handler returns, free(req.body_heap)                                                            │
  │ connection_thread        │                                                                                                       │
  └──────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  No changes to chttp_parse_request, no changes to any handler or parse_multipart — they all just read req->body which will now point at
  a larger buffer transparently.

  One question — upload size cap

  Since we're allocating based on the client-supplied Content-Length, we should cap it. What size limit makes sense for your NAS use case
   — something like 256 MB per upload, or do you want it effectively unlimited?

